            </div>
            <div class="col">
                <h2>Abigail Williams used her place as the first accused and confessed witch to claw herself into a place of power.</h2>
                <p>Abigail keeps her power over the other girls by threatening "And mark this. Let either of you breathe a word, or the edge of a word, about the other things, and I will come to you in the black of some terrible night and I will bring a pointy reckoning that will shudder you. And you know I can do it; I saw Indians smash my dear parents’ heads on the pillow next to mine, and I have seen some reddish work done at night, and I can make you wish you had never seen the sun go down!" (Miller 20) This allows her to keep control of what the other girls say and to who they say it.  This creates a situation where she has control over a majority of the witnesses of the crime of witchcraft and therefor, she has the most power in the town to either prove or disprove anyone guilty of witchcraft.  Abigail shows that she knows how much power she has by openly threatening Judge Danforth “Let you beware, Mr. Danforth. Think you to be so mighty that the power of Hell may not turn your wits? Beware of it!" (Miller 108) After she has control of the court, she uses it to get revenge on many people who have wronged her.  No one, even the “witches” themselves don’t know who will be accused next.</p>
